ate Data Centre. There is a plan to create a network of all 500 kiosks in villages and 177 existing taluka centres. Presently, a few centres have been provided with touch screen computers, but it is planned to provide this facility to all centres. On a pilot basis, two villages \u2013 Arudhi and Sassalu in Doddaballapura taluka \u2013 have been linked to taluka centres through mobile wireless sets (using Dak Netiii). Also, 200 Simputersiv have iii DakNet uses wireless technology in conjunction with the existing infrastructure, such as a post office, a cybercaf\u00e9 or kiosk, to extend connectivity to neighbouring areas. It uses point-to-point links between kiosks and mobile access points which are storage and transmission devices mounted on and powered by vehicles such as a bus or a bicycle. iv The Simputer is a small handheld computer, intended to bring computing power to the masses of India and other developing countries. The word \u201cSimputer\u201d is an acronym for \u201csimple, inexpensive and multilingual people\u2019s computer\u201d, and is a trademark of the Simputer Trust. Similar in appearance to the Palm Pilot class of handheld computers, the touch sensitive screen is operated with a stylus. Information and Communications Technology for Governance and Poverty Reduction 52 Human Interest Stories At last, relief after eight months Forty-year-old Gangu Muthaiyya, a landless labourer and member of a marginalized community, lives 25 km from Bangalore in a small village called", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "e815a900-d491-4440-a27d-41d4fe64a623": {"__data__": {"id_": "e815a900-d491-4440-a27d-41d4fe64a623", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/empowering-poor", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Progr